---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import rates from '../data/rates.json';
import sector from '../data/sector.json';

const R25 = rates.years['2025-26'];
const R26 = rates.years['2026-27'];
const H = rates.company_headlines_26_27;
const prev = rates.previous_year_context;

const pct = (a, b) => (((b - a) / a) * 100).toFixed(1);
const fmt = (n, d = 2) => '£' + n.toFixed(d);
const sign = (n) => (parseFloat(n) > 0 ? '+' : '') + n + '%';

const rows = [
  { label: 'Water supply, per cubic metre', a: R25.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, b: R26.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, dp: 3 },
  { label: 'Water supply, annual standing charge', a: R25.water_supply_standing_gbp, b: R26.water_supply_standing_gbp, dp: 2 },
  { label: 'Wastewater, per cubic metre', a: R25.wastewater_per_cubic_metre_gbp, b: R26.wastewater_per_cubic_metre_gbp, dp: 3 },
  { label: 'Wastewater, annual standing charge', a: R25.wastewater_standing_gbp, b: R26.wastewater_standing_gbp, dp: 2 },
  { label: 'Surface water drainage, annual', a: R25.surface_water_drainage_gbp, b: R26.surface_water_drainage_gbp, dp: 2 }
];

const waterM3Delta = pct(R25.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, R26.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp);
const waterStandingDelta = pct(R25.water_supply_standing_gbp, R26.water_supply_standing_gbp);
---

<Base title="The rise" currentPath="/" dek="What happened to your 2026 Southern Water bill">
  <h1 class="hed">
    Your bill went up by about a third on water supply this April.
    <span class="small">The company's headline is eight per cent. Both are true at the same time. Here is how.</span>
  </h1>

  <p class="lead">
    Published 18 April 2026. All figures are taken from primary sources. Every claim on this page is numbered and linked to the <a href="/sources">sources</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>The new rates, set against last year</h2>

  <p>
    These are Southern Water's own published rates<a class="cite" href="/sources#1">1</a> for metered households, for the year from 1 April 2026 to 31 March 2027.
  </p>

  <table class="rates-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th scope="col">Charge</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">2025-26</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">2026-27</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">Change</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {rows.map(r => {
        const d = pct(r.a, r.b);
        const up = parseFloat(d) > 0;
        return (
          <tr>
            <td>{r.label}</td>
            <td class="num">{fmt(r.a, r.dp)}</td>
            <td class="num">{fmt(r.b, r.dp)}</td>
            <td class={`num delta ${up ? '' : 'delta-down'}`}>{sign(d)}</td>
          </tr>
        );
      })}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Why you can hear two different numbers and both be right</h2>

  <p>
    Southern Water says the average combined household bill is going up by {H.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#2">2</a>. That is an average across three types of customer:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Combined water and wastewater: about {sign(H.combined_average_rise_pct)}, or {fmt(H.combined_average_monthly_rise_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2">2</a></li>
    <li>Water supply only: {sign(H.water_supply_only_rise_pct)}, or {fmt(H.water_supply_only_monthly_rise_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2">2</a></li>
    <li>Wastewater only: {sign(H.wastewater_only_rise_pct)}, a saving of about {fmt(H.wastewater_only_monthly_saving_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2">2</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Per cubic metre of water supply, the rate is up by {waterM3Delta} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#1">1</a>. The standing charge is up by {waterStandingDelta} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#1">1</a>. Whether your personal bill shows a rise of 8 per cent or closer to 30 depends on which services you get, how much water you use, and whether the billing period crosses 1 April.
  </p>

  <p class="callout">
    This comes a year after a {prev.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent average household rise. That one was front-loaded to pay for investment, the company said.<a class="cite" href="/sources#2">2</a>
  </p>

  <h2>Who approved this</h2>

  <p>
    Ofwat approved the increases as part of the PR24 Final Determination in December 2024, which sets price controls for every water company in England and Wales for 2025-2030<a class="cite" href="/sources#3">3</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Southern Water appealed, along with four other companies. They did not argue the determination was too high. They argued it was too low. The Competition and Markets Authority published its final redeterminations on 26 March 2026<a class="cite" href="/sources#4">4</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Household customers cannot appeal Ofwat's decision directly. Ofwat does not handle individual bill complaints. There is no retail market: you cannot switch supplier.
  </p>

  <h2>Dividends, with the nuance</h2>

  <p>
    Southern Water states that it has paid no dividends to external shareholders since 2017, and that Macquarie-managed funds have injected more than £1.6 billion of equity into the group since 2021<a class="cite" href="/sources#7">7</a>. Both of those claims check out. Ofwat's own Monitoring Financial Resilience Report for 2022-23 records a £1.1 billion equity injection in September 2021, of which £530 million reached the regulated entity, and a further £550 million in October 2023, of which £375 million reached the regulated entity<a class="cite" href="/sources#8">8</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    At sector level, things look different. Ofwat's most recent financial monitoring reports show total water-company borrowings of £{sector.sector.total_borrowing_31_march_2025_gbp_bn} billion at 31 March 2025<a class="cite" href="/sources#5">5</a>, up from net debt of £{sector.sector.net_debt_31_march_2024_gbp_bn} billion a year earlier<a class="cite" href="/sources#6">6</a>. The sector-wide dividend total for 2023-24 was about £{sector.sector.dividends_declared_2023_24_gbp_bn} billion<a class="cite" href="/sources#6">6</a>, with a new dividend-policy licence condition coming into force that year.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the position is: Southern Water specifically has been under dividend restrictions since 2017 and is now receiving fresh equity. The sector as a whole still carries debt of roughly £70 billion, and until 2023-24 had few meaningful constraints on how dividends linked to performance.
  </p>

  <h2>Is it fair? That is a different question from is it lawful.</h2>

  <p>
    The rise is lawful. Ofwat approved it. The CMA heard the appeal. A lawful outcome is not automatically a fair one, and fairness is not a question for Ofwat or the CMA. It is a question for Parliament.
  </p>

  <p>
    An individual complaint about your bill goes to Southern Water. It might get you a breakdown, a social tariff, or a meter test. It will not change the rates. The structural question, about who should pay for investment that was not funded when it should have been, goes to your MP.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="btn primary" href="/complain">Draft a complaint to Southern Water</a>
    <a class="btn ghost" href="/write-to-mp">Write to your MP</a>
  </div>

  <div class="flag">
    <strong>This site is not a campaign.</strong> It does not tell you what to conclude and does not suggest you stop paying. Non-payment has real consequences for your credit rating and is not recommended without advice. If you are struggling, Southern Water's social tariff gives at least a 45 per cent discount for eligible households<a class="cite" href="/sources#12">12</a>.
  </div>
</Base>
